---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const proofPoints = [
  {
    label: 'Engine fidelity',
    text: 'Navigation, forms, timers, and script behavior are driven by the engine instead of being faked in the UI.'
  },
  {
    label: 'Desktop host',
    text: 'Waves gives the project a desktop browser you can actually use for examples, testing, and live sessions.'
  },
  {
    label: 'Protocol realism',
    text: 'Transport stays separate from the runtime, so network constraints can be tested without muddying engine behavior.'
  }
];

---

<Layout>
  <main class="page-shell">
    <header class="hero">
      <div class="hero-copy">
        <p class="kicker">WaveNav Labs</p>
        <h1>A desktop browser for the early mobile web.</h1>
        <p class="lede">
          Waves is a desktop WAP/WML browser built for people who want to explore, test, and improve
          this stack without fighting vague emulation or throwaway demos.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
          <a class="button" href="./simulator/">Open Simulator</a>
          <a class="button button-secondary" href="https://github.com/dills122/wap-labs">View GitHub</a>
        </div>
        <ul class="hero-proof" aria-label="Key project qualities">
          {
            proofPoints.map((point) => (
              <li>
                <strong>{point.label}</strong>
                <span>{point.text}</span>
              </li>
            ))
          }
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="hero-stage" aria-label="Waves product screenshots">
        <figure class="stage-card stage-card-primary">
          <img
            src="./waves-local-forms-example.png"
            alt="Waves rendering a WML form example with editable fields and event timeline"
            loading="eager"
          />
          <figcaption>Local mode with working examples, forms, and runtime inspection.</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure class="stage-card stage-card-accent">
          <img
            src="./waves-network-page-with-links.png"
            alt="Waves showing a network-rendered WML page with selectable links"
          />
          <figcaption>Live pages still feel like WAP, but are much easier to inspect and debug.</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="content-grid">
      <article class="panel panel-feature">
        <p class="section-tag">Why it exists</p>
        <h2>Most WAP tooling is either inaccurate, unfinished, or painful to work with.</h2>
        <p>
          Waves is meant to be the practical middle ground: close enough to the original platform to
          be worth trusting, but modern enough to support debugging, iteration, and real development work.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="panel">
        <p class="section-tag">Stack</p>
        <h2>Layered by design</h2>
        <ul class="detail-list">
          <li><strong>Gateway</strong><span>Kannel and the surrounding environment for compatibility testing.</span></li>
          <li><strong>Transport</strong><span>WBXML, WSP/WTP behavior, and the fetch rules that sit underneath the browser.</span></li>
          <li><strong>Engine</strong><span>The Rust/WASM runtime that parses WML, handles navigation, and renders cards.</span></li>
          <li><strong>Waves</strong><span>The desktop host that ties everything together into a usable browser experience.</span></li>
        </ul>
      </article>

      <article class="panel">
        <p class="section-tag">Inside Waves</p>
        <h2>Waves is becoming a real browser, not just a test harness.</h2>
        <p>
          You can load local examples, browse live pages, and inspect session state, snapshots, timelines,
          and transport behavior without leaving the app.
        </p>
        <p><a class="inline-link" href="./simulator/">Launch the simulator</a></p>
      </article>

      <article class="panel panel-wide">
        <p class="section-tag">What is shipping now</p>
        <h2>Recent work has made Waves much more practical to use.</h2>
        <div class="milestone-grid">
          <div>
            <h3>Interaction</h3>
            <p>Text inputs, select controls, and form submission now work through the engine and browser together.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3>Responsiveness</h3>
            <p>Slow startup and failed fetches no longer tie up the whole UI the way they used to.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3>Determinism</h3>
            <p>History replay, payload limits, and key runtime paths now have stronger behavioral coverage.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="gallery-band">
      <article class="gallery-copy">
        <p class="section-tag">Real states</p>
        <h2>Waves stays clear in both loading and failure states.</h2>
        <p>
          It can load local examples, follow live links, and still tell you what is happening when
          startup is slow or a network request fails.
        </p>
      </article>

      <figure class="gallery-shot">
        <img
          src="./waves-network-loading.png"
          alt="Waves waiting for its first network deck render while keeping the interface visible"
        />
        <figcaption>The loading state keeps the shell visible instead of collapsing into a blank wait.</figcaption>
      </figure>

      <figure class="gallery-shot">
        <img
          src="./waves-network-error.png"
          alt="Waves showing a network error state in the desktop shell"
        />
        <figcaption>Failures are surfaced as part of the product, not as a frozen or blocked app.</figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <section class="cta-band">
      <div>
        <p class="section-tag">Next step</p>
        <h2>Try Waves first, then dig into the stack behind it.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="cta-actions">
        <a class="button" href="./simulator/">Open Simulator</a>
        <a class="button button-secondary" href="https://github.com/dills122/wap-labs/tree/main/browser">Browse Browser Source</a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <footer class="footer">
      <p>WaveNav Labs · WAP/WML browser, runtime, and protocol tooling</p>
    </footer>
  </main>
</Layout>
